iocs.title: Artifact Flagged by Antivirus
iocs.description: An antivirus engine flagged an artifact as potentially malicious. This may be a false positive as antivirus programs will also flag packed or encrypted software with a signature. Please confirm the file is indeed malicious. Checking other indicators and outbound communications will help to confirm this.

iocs.title: PDF Contains Embedded Microsoft Office Document Stream
iocs.description: A PDF document was found that contains an embedded Microsoft Office stream. The PDF specification allows embedding files within a PDF document. JavaScript is used to extract and open documents embedded within a PDF, which are often saved to a temporary directory.

iocs.title: PDF Contains JavaScript Which Uses the ExportDataObject() Function
iocs.description: PDF contains an embedded JavaScript which called the "exportDataObject" function. The 'exportDataObject()' function is used to extract an embedded document and launch it using the default Windows program for the file extension. This function could be used to open a malicious Office document or zip archive.

iocs.title: VBA Macro Opens a Binary File
iocs.description: A VBA macro was discovered that opens a file in binary mode. Office files support a modified form of VisualBasic that can perform operations on a document. In this case, a file is opened with the particular instruction that it should be treated as a binary file. This is not necessarily malicious; legitimate documents may do this to read customized data files or configurations. Malicious documents may use this to store their own configurations, create executables or encode external files.

iocs.title: Antivirus Service Flagged Artifact As Containing A Macro
iocs.description: An antivirus service flagged an artifact as containing a macro. Many document formats support a macro programming language that allows macro programs to be embedded within documents to produce dynamic content or perform other actions. Microsoft Office files support a modified form of VisualBasic that can perform operations on a document. PDF documents support JavaScript as a macro language. Macro programs are not necessarily malicious. Legitimate uses include auto-saving a document, loading the latest data from a remote file, among others. Malware often uses macros as a springboard, launching other processes when the user opens or closes the document.

iocs.title: VBA Macro Has Action on Open
iocs.description: A VBA macro was discovered that uses a function to perform an action when its parent document is opened. Office files support a modified form of VisualBasic that can perform operations on a document. In this case, it has hooked a function that is called when the Office program or document is opened. This is not necessarily malicious. Legitimate uses include pulling in the latest data from an external source, alerting the user of the last modified time and so on. Malware uses this as a launch point to execute external programs as soon as the malicious document is opened. Check the artifact data for further information.

iocs.title: VBA Macro Reads Environment Variables
iocs.description: A VBA macro was discovered that loads environment variables. Office files support a modified form of VisualBasic that can perform operations on a document. In this case, the macro requests an environment variable using the 'Environ' command. This is not necessarily malicious. Legitimate uses include determining where to save a file, automatically marking the last person who modified the file and so on. Malware may use this to gather basic information about the system, such as operating system, processor information, home directory, etc.

iocs.title: Artifact Flagged Malicious by Antivirus Service
iocs.description: An antivirus service flagged an artifact as malicious. When using antivirus software, relying on a single engine is susceptible to false-positives. Online services, such as VirusTotal and Reversing Labs, use multiple antivirus engines to scan a file and the scan results of all engines are taken together to make a more accurate determination. One or more of these services have indicated that the file is malicious with a high degree of confidence. The results of individual antivirus engine scans are displayed, if available.

iocs.title: PDF Contains an Open Action
iocs.description: The OpenAction Key specifies a destination that will be displayed or an action that will be performed when the document is opened. Attackers will embed malicious scripts with the PDF document where the payload automatically executes when the document is opened.

iocs.title: EICAR File Detected
iocs.description: An EICAR file was detected in the sample. EICAR is a test file for anti-virus programs. The EICAR file itself is not malicious. Its presence is often indicative of a test program.

iocs.title: Document Flagged by Antivirus
iocs.description: An antivirus engine flagged a document. Documents are a common vector for delivering malware. Microsoft Office files support a modified form of VisualBasic that can perform operations on a document. In addition, malicious documents may attempt to exploit an underlying flaw in application that opens them to deliver malicious payloads.

iocs.title: PDF Contains Embedded JavaScript Action
iocs.description: A PDF was found that contains a JavaScript action. JavaScript actions may be triggered by opening the PDF, by clicking on an element within the document or interacting in some other way. JavaScript embedded within a PDF is often obfuscated in order to conceal its intentions from analysts or in an attempt to bypass Intrusion Detection Systems. Attackers will use JavaScript to interact with dynamic elements that execute on a machine.

iocs.title: Document Contains a Single Page
iocs.description: A document was found that contains only one page. Many document files embed various properties at a high level, which makes them easy to parse and display within Windows. These can include the number of pages or words, the last modified time and so on. Many malicious documents contain only a single page or a very low word count. However, these properties should not be solely relied on, as they are easy to manipulate or erase.

iocs.title: A Machine Learning Model Identified a PDF as Possible Phishing
iocs.description: A machine learning model has determined that one or more PDF artifacts contain phishing characteristics. The machine learning model is trained on a very large number of samples. The output of the training is a decision engine that takes static features of PDF artifacts as input and returns a verdict on whether the contents are a likely phishing attempt. In general, a single feature of the file will not cause it to be determined as phishing, but rather the decision engine uses many characteristics of the artifact together to come up with a verdict.

iocs.title: Process Modified File in a User Directory
iocs.description: Malware will modify files in user directories to hide logs or other evidence. Also, by modifying various files it can disable functionality in the system which may detect or hamper the operation of the malware. Lastly, it may be attempting to hide an executable, so that it appears to be a legitimate file. Please review the 'Disk Artifacts' section in order to view additional details about this file.

iocs.title: Office Document Contains a VBA Macro
iocs.description: A Microsoft Office document was found that contains embedded macros. Office files support a modified form of VisualBasic that can perform operations on a document. Macros are not necessarily malicious. Legitimate uses include auto-saving a document, loading the latest data from a remote file and so on. Malware often uses macros as a springboard, launching other processes when the user opens or closes the document.

iocs.title: Decoy Document Detected
iocs.description: Phishing attacks include some type of Lure to trick the victim into performing an activity such as clicking on a link or opening a file attachment. The lure relies on social engineering concepts to convince the victim that the lure is genuine and its instructions should be followed. Phishing attacks will often embed a decoy document, relevant to the lure being used. In this way as the exploitation of a vulnerability takes place a decoy document is displayed to the victim in an attempt to avoid raising suspicion.

iocs.title: PDF Contains Embedded JavaScript Stream
iocs.description: A PDF was found that contains JavaScript. PDF contains several situations that allow actions driven by JavaScript. These actions could include opening the document, scrolling to a certain page, mouse-over an object, etc. The presence of JavaScript is not necessarily malicious. Malware can use the automatic launch of the JavaScript to launch attacks on opening the PDF. Other attacks may use social-engineering to encourage the user to do specific actions to avoid sandbox execution.

iocs.title: Document Contains Embedded Material and Minimal Content
iocs.description: A document was discovered that has very few words and pages. In addition, the document contains scripts or embedded content. The combination of these two anomalies makes this document highly suspicious.

iocs.title: Highly Suspicious PDF Exporting Data Object with Antivirus Flagged Artifact
iocs.description: PDF contains embedded JavaScript that references the "exportDataObject" function. The "exportDataObject" function is used to extract an embedded document and launch it using the default Windows program for the file extension. While the inclusion of this function is not a clear sign of maliciousness, an antivirus engine has also flagged one of the artifacts in the sample as potentially malicious. These two indicators combined have been found to be strongly associated with malware.
